---
import "../../styles/global.css";
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import Callout from "../../components/docs/Callout/Callout.astro";
import Screenshot from "../../components/docs/Screenshot/Screenshot.astro";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Command logs — Arris Docs"
  breadcrumbs={[{ label: "Docs", href: "/" }, { label: "Querying" }, { label: "Command logs" }]}
  heading="Command logs"
  lede="A live, session-scoped log of every command you run — queries, dbt and SQLMesh runs, and Python — with output, status, and timing."
  tocItems={[
    { label: "Overview", href: "#overview" },
    { label: "Opening the panel", href: "#opening" },
    { label: "What a log entry shows", href: "#entry" },
    { label: "Filtering & clearing", href: "#filtering" },
    { label: "Session-only, never persisted", href: "#persistence" },
  ]}
  currentPath="/querying/command-logs"
  prev={{ label: "Results viewer", href: "/querying/results", section: "Querying" }}
  next={{ label: "Cross-source queries", href: "/querying/cross-source", section: "Querying" }}
>
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>

  <p>
    Command logs is a running record of the commands you execute during a session. Every run
    appends an entry with its output, status, and timing, so you can see at a glance what ran, how
    long it took, and whether it succeeded. It covers four kinds of command:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>SQL</strong> &mdash; queries run from console tabs and SQL files.</li>
    <li><strong>dbt</strong> &mdash; <code>run</code>, <code>test</code>, <code>build</code>, <code>compile</code>, and other dbt commands.</li>
    <li><strong>SQLMesh</strong> &mdash; <code>plan</code>, <code>test</code>, <code>render</code>, and related commands.</li>
    <li><strong>Python</strong>: cells run in a Jupyter notebook.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Schema browsing, opening files, and UI navigation are not commands and are not logged.
  </p>

  <Screenshot
    src="/screenshots/command-logs.png"
    alt="The Arris Command Logs panel listing recent SQL runs newest-first, with a failed query expanded to show its raw output error and raw query, plus a filter box and status dropdown"
    caption="The Command Logs panel lists each run newest-first; expand an entry to see its raw output and query."
  />

  <h2 id="opening">Opening the panel</h2>

  <p>
    Command logs live in the bottom pane, alongside the results. Click the <strong>Command Logs</strong>
    tab in the results footer to show it. The pane surfaces automatically whenever a command runs,
    so a long dbt build or query streams its output into view as it happens.
  </p>

  <h2 id="entry">What a log entry shows</h2>

  <p>
    Each entry has a header that is always visible:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Status</strong> &mdash; a spinner while running, then a check on success or a cross on error.</li>
    <li><strong>Command</strong> &mdash; a one-line label: the SQL text, the dbt or SQLMesh command, or the first line of Python.</li>
    <li><strong>Source tab</strong> &mdash; a badge naming the tab the command came from.</li>
    <li><strong>Duration</strong> &mdash; how long the command took, once it finishes.</li>
    <li><strong>Timestamp</strong> &mdash; the wall-clock time it started.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Click an entry to expand its body. The newest entry is expanded by default. The body shows:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Per-node breakdown</strong> &mdash; for dbt and SQLMesh runs, a table of each node with its type, status, and duration.</li>
    <li><strong>Raw output</strong> &mdash; the verbatim console output, with ANSI colors preserved.</li>
    <li><strong>Full query</strong> &mdash; for SQL entries, the executed statement, with a toggle to expand long queries.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="filtering">Filtering & clearing</h2>

  <p>
    A search box filters entries by command text or output, and a status dropdown narrows to
    running, succeeded, or failed commands. <strong>Clear logs</strong> empties the panel. Entries
    are listed newest first.
  </p>

  <Callout type="note" title="Read-only entries">
    Command logs is a record, not a launcher. Entries cannot be re-run, loaded back into the
    editor, or exported from the panel. To re-run something, run it again from its tab.
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="persistence">Session-only, never persisted</h2>

  <p>
    The log lives in memory for the current session only. It is never written to disk, never sent
    anywhere, and has no retention setting. Quitting and reopening Arris starts with an empty log,
    and clearing the panel discards every entry immediately.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
